<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 1 日，星期二 21:01:54 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Countries Raid Each Others’ Health Systems in Global Battle for Nurses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>医疗人员短缺导致全球范围内猖獗的偷猎行为，激怒了较贫穷的国家<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826463/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="性健康医生哈迪普·康 (Hardeep Kang) 医生在澳大利亚凯恩斯的新工作中，在一家英国招聘机构与她接洽后，她搬到了那里。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>性健康医生哈迪普·康 (Hardeep Kang) 医生在澳大利亚凯恩斯的新工作中，在一家英国招聘机构与她接洽后，她搬到了那里。华尔街日报的布莱恩·<span>凯西 华尔街日报的布莱恩·凯西</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093125"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093125"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stuart-condie" itemprop="url" rel="author">斯图尔特·康迪</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 1 日下午 4:34（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>全球医疗保健工作者短缺正在引发一场激烈的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/high-pay-for-covid-19-nurses-leads-to-shortages-at-some-hospitals-11630253483?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球人才争夺战</a>，富裕国家纷纷从其他国家的医疗系统中寻找工作人员来照顾老龄化人口。</p><p>这项竞赛帮助美国和澳大利亚等国家替换了一些在Covid-19大流行最严重期间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-surge-leaves-doctors-nurses-reeling-from-burnout-11611612044?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞职的</a>护士。但这也让发展中国家和英国等一些富裕国家的医院处境更糟，因为它们的员工流向了工资更高的国家。</p><p>澳大利亚一直是最激进的偷猎者之一，提供特别奖金和快速签证。去年冬天，澳大利亚在不列颠群岛进行了一场广告活动，广告中的工人身后的窗户洒满了阳光。此次活动恰逢英国护士因工资、长时间工作和其他问题而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-nurses-stage-biggest-ever-strike-as-health-system-strains-11671121289?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">举行罢工</a>。</p><p> “你可以在清晨冲浪，周末去飞蝇钓鱼，参加摄影课程，写小说，或者在农贸市场出售蜜饯，”行业杂志《英国医学杂志》上的一则急救药物广告说道。登记员的工作。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>投放这则广告的澳大利亚塔斯马尼亚州卫生部门表示，与其他地方当局一样，该部门正在向包括英国在内的许多国家寻找海外工人。</p><p>这场战斗是今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-worlds-biggest-economies-cautiously-open-their-doors-to-more-foreign-workers-664c3549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">全球移民潮复苏</a>的一部分，这场移民潮正在重塑世界经济。自疫情最严重时期以来，随着边境重新开放，各国一直欢迎特定行业的外国工人，以解决劳动力短缺问题，帮助将移民人数推至创纪录水平。</p><p>津巴布韦圭鲁省医院的护士道格拉斯·奇科布武(Douglas Chikobvu)表示，近年来，他看到外科病房的大约十几名护士搬到国外工作。</p><p>津巴布韦专业护士联盟秘书长 Chikobvu 表示，在一些医院，一名护士有时在轮班期间要照顾 25 或 30 名患者，而不是更合理的 10 名患者。医生被迫取消手术因为他们没有足够的员工。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826697?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">护士道格拉斯·奇科布武 (Douglas Chikobvu) 表示，护士们已经离开津巴布韦到国外工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826789?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">六月，护士们在津巴布韦一家医院外示威，要求提高工资。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：aaron ufumeli/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>津巴布韦副总统康斯坦丁诺·奇文加</p>身兼卫生部长的他四月份威胁说，他的国家将通过一项新法律，将积极招募津巴布韦医护人员定为犯罪行为。<p></p><p>英国政府今年公布的数据显示，截至 3 月 31 日的 12 个月内，仅英国就向津巴布韦国民发放了 17,421 份医疗和护理人员签证，几乎是前 12 个月的六倍。</p><p>奇温加在四月份的一次关于人口贩运的活动上发表讲话时，将招募发展中国家医务人员称为“反人类罪”。</p><p>他说：“如果人们因为没有护士和医生而死在医院，而且有人如此不负责任地不培训自己的国民，而是希望贫穷国家为他们提供培训，那么这就是一种必须严肃对待的犯罪行为。”</p><p>世界卫生组织今年 3 月公布了 55 个国家（其中 37 个在非洲）面临最紧迫的卫生劳动力挑战的名单。这些国家平均每 10,000 人只有 15 名卫生工作者，而高收入国家每 10,000 人有 148 名卫生工作者。</p><p>世界卫生组织已要求其成员国在未首先签署双边协议以支持招募国家的情况下，不要积极从这 55 个国家招募医生和护士。此类支持可能包括资助新员工的培训或计划让卫生工作者在几年后返回原籍国。</p><p>对于富裕国家来说，吸引国外医务人员很有吸引力，因为培训护士和医生可能需要数年时间。 《健康事务》杂志的一项研究显示，2020 年至 2021 年间， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nurse-shortage-hospitals-hiring-gig-economy-dc94bdb2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">美国失去了超过 10 万名护士</a>，这是有记录以来的最大降幅。</p><p>自疫情最严重以来，医院一直在努力重建正常的人员配备水平和士气。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nurses-flock-back-to-hospitals-after-leaving-in-the-pandemic-4f94b591?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">此后，工资和工作条件的改善吸引了一些工人回来</a>，但短缺仍然存在。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826724?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">道格拉斯·奇科布武 (Douglas Chikobvu) 前往津巴布韦圭鲁省医院工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826698?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">道格拉斯·奇科布武 (Douglas Chikobvu) 在家里挂着制服，他说，在津巴布韦的一些医院，一名护士一个班次就可以照顾 25 到 30 名患者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据澳大利亚统计局的最新数据，在澳大利亚，从 2020 年初到 2022 年 8 月，广告中的卫生专业人员职位空缺数量增加了一倍多，并在 9 个月后仍接近历史峰值。</p><p>根据澳大利亚内政部的数据，截至 2023 年 3 月的 9 个月内，该国向医护人员发放了 4,950 份签证。官员们表示，这个数字比一年前增加了 48%，但该国仍然面临护士短缺的问题。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/RHC" class="">Ramsay Health Care</a>在澳大利亚和其他 10 个国家拥有 500 多家医院和诊所<span class="company-name-type">，</span>该公司最近表示，技术工人的缺乏继续限制了其治疗患者的能力。据称，该公司正在海外寻找员工。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>性健康医生哈迪普·康 (Hardeep Kang) 医生正在英国北部工作，一家招聘机构找到她，询问她是否有兴趣搬到澳大利亚。 11 月移居澳大利亚后，她现在在凯恩斯工作，凯恩斯是澳大利亚北部的一个城市，被称为通往大堡礁的门户。</p><p>康说，她现在的年收入比在英国高出约 56,000 美元，部分原因是州政府为改善大城市以外的职位而提供补贴。她每天的通勤方式是沿着海滨骑自行车。</p><p>一月份从爱尔兰搬到澳大利亚的放射科医生丽贝卡·戴利 (Rebekah Daly) 表示，由于与新冠病毒相关的旅行限制已经取消，她在家乡的同事中近四分之一已经辞职去海外旅行或工作，这增加了这些人的工作量被留下来。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="909" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826464?width=1260&amp;height=909" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">自行车是 Hardeep Kang 博士在澳大利亚日常通勤的一部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的布莱恩·卡西</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="905" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826737?width=1260&amp;height=905" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">她说她现在在澳大利亚的年收入比在英国多约 56,000 美元</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的布莱恩·卡西</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>英国为医疗保健工作者推出了新签证，其规定比其他技术工人的繁琐规定要少。根据政府数据，截至 3 月 31 日的 12 个月内，该国向医疗和护理人员发放了 101,570 份签证，几乎是去年的三倍，其中大多数新员工来自印度、尼日利亚和津巴布韦。</p><p>世界卫生组织名单公布后，英国政府表示，卫生和社会保健组织不会积极从该机构标记的国家招募人员，但没有什么可以阻止这些国家的卫生工作者申请空缺职位。</p><p>爱尔兰在大流行之前严重依赖海外卫生工作者，去年放宽了对已在该国的非欧洲医生的就业限制，作为留住他们的努力的一部分。</p><p>据世界卫生组织称，近年来已有 70 多个国家出台了法律，以方便从国外聘用卫生工作者。德国等其他富裕国家已将招募医护人员作为高层访问加纳、巴西和阿尔巴尼亚等国的一部分。</p><p>在美国， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/green-card-backlog-fuels-shortage-of-nurses-at-hospitals-nursing-homes-4f0b0e44?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">从国外招募护士实际上已经停止</a>，因为医疗机构用来雇用护士的绿卡类型已经被超额认购，以至于国务院停止处理申请。截至 9 月份的过去两个财年，包括注册护士和职业护士在内的海外医疗工作者的签证筛查请求均增长了 40% 以上。</p><p>总部位于纽约的 Adex Medical Staffing 招聘总监贾斯汀·莱博维茨 (Justin Leibowitz) 表示，积压意味着今年夏天招聘的护士可能需要长达四年的时间才能在美国开始工作，这使美国的人力资源公司和医疗保健雇主在全球范围内处于不利地位。</p><p> Adex 预先投入资金帮助国际护士满足在美国工作的要求，但直到护士开始工作后，该公司才能收回这笔资金。他表示，这些延误要求该公司需要等待更长的时间才能获得投资回报。国际护士也可能会重新考虑他们的选择。</p><p>莱博维茨表示，随着联邦财政年度的开始，绿卡积压情况可能会有所缓解，这可能会改善招聘前景。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>全球医疗资源短缺问题该如何解决？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>一些发展中国家正在采取措施，加大卫生工作者移民的难度。</p><p>长期以来，许多医护人员都流失到美国，菲律宾在疫情期间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-heightens-global-struggle-for-migrant-nurses-11588161393?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">实施了临时禁令，禁止更多医护人员离开</a>。它继续限制可以在海外工作的人数，尽管这样做会剥夺该国急需的汇款收入。</p><p>尼日利亚立法者正在考虑一项法案，要求医生在家工作至少五年才能获准移民。</p><p>负责监督人员配置的津巴布韦卫生服务委员会表示，该国需要 81,517 名医护人员才能满足人口需求，但截至去年 9 月，该国仅有 74,298 名医护人员。</p><p>津巴布韦圭鲁省医院的护士 Chikobvu 表示，他和同事在专门的 WhatsApp 群组中分享美国和英国等国家的招聘广告。</p><p>尽管看到了他的国家医疗人才流失的影响，奇科布武目前正在美国申请护理工作，并反对限制富裕国家从贫穷国家雇用护士。</p><p>他说，他的月收入约为 425 美元，不足以支付家人的食品和医疗费用，也不足以支付四个孩子的学费。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826712?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">道格拉斯·奇科布武 (Douglas Chikobvu) 和他的女儿在津巴布韦。某护士工会秘书长称，目前正在美国申请护士工作</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> ——梅兰妮·埃文斯对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Stuart Condie <a href="mailto:stuart.condie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（stuart.condie@wsj.com）</a>和 Gabriele Steinhauser（ <a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gabriele.steinhauser@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 20:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429<author><![CDATA[Stuart CondieGabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>拉姆齐医疗保健</category><category>澳大利亚RHC</category><category>澳大利亚：RHC</category><category>道格拉斯·奇科布武</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tensions Between Russian, Western Allies Grow Over Niger Coup]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>西非国家选边站，欧洲国家从尼日尔撤离公民<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100512"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827574?width=700&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，法国国民聚集在一起等待从尼日尔空运。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100512"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/noemie-bisserbe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Noemie Bisserbe</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Benoit Faucon</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gabriele Steinhauser</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 1 日下午 2:48（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尼日尔上周发生<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-general-declares-himself-leader-as-russian-mercenary-hails-coup-d47efa68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">政变，引发莫斯科在该</a>地区的盟友与与美国和其他西方大国合作更密切的国家之间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的紧张对峙，</a>随后欧洲各国政府于周二开始从尼日尔撤离本国公民。</p><p>由尼日尔前殖民国家法国领导的撤离行动表明，欧洲各国政府预计其公民在该国面临更高的风险，这对于美国打击萨赫勒地区伊斯兰武装分子的努力<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">至关重要</a>。萨赫勒地区是撒哈拉以南的半干旱地带。 。</p><p>西方官员担心，上周拘留尼日尔当选总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆的军政府可能会<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-need-of-allies-putin-courts-african-leaders-in-st-petersburg-b6596a7b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯发展更密切的关系</a>，特别是如果法国和美国削减对军政府的军事援助。周日，数千名支持政变的抗议者向法国驻首都尼亚美大使馆投掷石块，其中一些人挥舞着俄罗斯国旗和标语牌，要求法国退出尼日尔。</p><p> “鉴于尼亚美的局势、前天针对我国大使馆发生的暴力事件以及领空的关闭，导致我们的同胞无法通过自己的方式离开该国，法国正在准备撤离其国民，希望离开该国的欧洲国民，”法国外交部周二表示。 “疏散行动将于今天开始，”它补充道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827265?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">抗议者举着从法国驻尼亚美大使馆拿走的标语。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>意大利外交部长安东尼奥·塔亚尼(Antonio Tajani)在社交媒体平台X（前身为Twitter）上表示，意大利政府将派遣一架航班飞往尼亚美，帮助意大利国民离开该国。</p><p>白宫国家安全委员会发言人约翰·柯比表示，目前没有从尼日尔撤离美国公民的计划。</p><p>柯比说：“我们确实是每小时都在关注这一情况，如果我们必须做出调整，我们就会做出调整——只是我们现在不在那儿。”</p><p>近年来，美国政府斥资约 5 亿美元武装尼日尔军队，并在该国驻扎了约 1,100 名士兵和无人机。</p><p>这场由尼日尔强大的总统卫队领导的政变暴露了西非邻国之间的深刻分歧，其中几个邻国的民选政府在最近几周也被军队推翻。</p><p>西非国家经济共同体（以非洲最大经济体尼日利亚为主导，与尼日尔接壤 1,000 英里的边界）的领导人都大力支持巴祖姆。该组织被称为西非经济共同体，对尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">实施严厉的金融和贸易制裁</a>，并表示，如果军政府未能在本周末之前恢复巴祖姆的权力，他们将考虑进行军事干预。</p><p>这一威胁促使马里和布基纳法索（尼日尔的两个邻国在政变后与莫斯科结盟）的军事领导人发出警告，称他们将帮助保卫尼日尔军政府免受西非经共体的干预。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9B8EB2F8-7751-46ED-8D36-E964233A2505&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffrance-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯周六表示，尼日尔的军事政变危及了美国价值数亿美元的援助和安全支持。达伦·英格兰/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>美国苏丹问题特使前幕僚长卡梅伦·哈德森表示，双方可能都在虚张声势地谈论军事对抗，双方都对更广泛的地区冲突不感兴趣。</p><p>哈德森说，马里和布基纳法索已经在本国边境与圣战武装分子作战，而国内也反对对尼日利亚军队进行武装干预，而尼日利亚军队必须领导这样的任务。他说，尽管如此，马里和布基纳法索的警告“提高了西非经共体干预的风险和成本”，并凸显了莫斯科对该地区的控制。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>法国外交部长</p>凯瑟琳·科隆纳周一否认了尼日尔军政府关于巴黎将参与军事干预的说法。 “法国唯一的优先事项是其国民的安全，”她在晚间电视采访中说。<p></p><p>科隆纳指责军政府和俄罗斯对法国大使馆的袭击负责。</p><p> “我们（周日）看到的是一场有组织的、非自发的、暴力的、极其危险的抗议活动，其中有燃烧瓶、俄罗斯国旗、反法口号，都是从我们在其他地方看到的复制粘贴的，”她说。 “所以所有常见的俄罗斯-非洲风格的不稳定因素都是如此。”</p><p>外交部官员表示，约有 1,200 名法国公民居住在尼日尔，尽管其中许多人目前正在国外度假。法国国防部表示，这一数字不包括驻扎在尼日尔并将留在那里的约 1,500 名法国士兵。</p><p>法国外交部官员表示，他们正在与美国就可能撤离美国公民的事宜进行联系。</p><p> 2013年，在社会党总统弗朗索瓦·奥朗德的领导下，法国向萨赫勒地区部署了军队，帮助打击伊斯兰国和与基地组织有联系的武装分子。在马里和布基纳法索发生政变后，它被迫缩减在尼日尔的存在，并将精力集中在巴祖姆的盟友尼日尔。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Michael M. Phillips 和 Gordon Lubold 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Noemie Bisserbe ( <a href="mailto:noemie.bisserbe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">noemie.bisserbe@wsj.com</a> )、Benoit Faucon ( <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a> ) 和 Gabriele Steinhauser ( <a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 18:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af<author><![CDATA[Noemie BisserbeBenoit FauconGabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>叛乱</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>叛乱</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Meta Platforms to Begin Blocking News for Canadian Users]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Facebook母公司表示，为了回应旨在补偿国内媒体的立法，这些变化将需要数周时间才能推出<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101891"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827696?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">这项名为《在线新闻法》的立法于六月获得加拿大议会的正式批准。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：拉尔夫·劳尔/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101891"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">保罗·维埃拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日下午 2:36 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-to-begin-blocking-news-for-canadian-users-35d35b2b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>渥太华——经过数月的警告后， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>周二表示，它已开始阻止加拿大 Facebook 和 Instagram 用户访问新闻链接，以回应强制数字平台向国内媒体机构提供补偿的立法。</p><p> Meta 发言人安迪·斯通 (Andy Stone) 在 X（该平台以前称为 Twitter）的官方账户上表示：“变化将在几周内推出。” “正如我们一直说的，法律是建立在一个根本上有缺陷的前提之上的。遗憾的是，我们合理遵守的唯一方法是停止在加拿大提供新闻。”</p><p>这项名为《 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-passes-law-forcing-facebook-google-to-pay-media-for-links-f3e13300?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在线新闻法》的</a>立法于六月获得加拿大议会的正式批准。 Meta 去年曾警告称，实施该法案将迫使其屏蔽其平台上的新闻报道，就像<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-day-facebook-went-dark-on-news-11613652431?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2021 年在澳大利亚所做的那样</a>。</p><p>谷歌的母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="">Alphabet</a>表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>一旦当局开始执行这项立法，该公司将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-to-block-canada-news-links-from-search-function-in-response-to-law-9fb56046?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">删除加拿大用户搜索功能上的新闻文章链接</a>，目前预计该立法将于今年年底实施。</p><p>加拿大参议院通过的新法律要求数字平台与新闻出版商就其内容达成商业协议，新闻出版商包括印刷媒体、在线媒体和广播媒体。目标是为媒体机构提供财务生命线，以抵消迁移到数字领域的广告收入损失。如果谈判失败，立法要求双方进行具有约束力的仲裁，以确定适当的赔偿。</p><p>记者未能立即联系到加拿大政府发言人置评。上个月，总理贾斯汀·特鲁多将与 Meta 和谷歌关于当地媒体赔偿问题的纠纷比作第二次世界大战。 7月5日，他对记者表示：“他们决定攻击加拿大，这是一个错误的选择。加拿大人不会被美国的亿万富翁欺负。”</p><p>写信给保罗·维埃拉 (Paul Vieira)： <a href="mailto:Paul.Vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Paul.Vieira@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 18:36:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-to-begin-blocking-news-for-canadian-users-35d35b2b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-to-begin-blocking-news-for-canadian-users-35d35b2b<author><![CDATA[Paul Vieira]]></author><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Replaces Missile Commander Days After Removing Foreign Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>分析人士称，罢免高级军事领导人旨在增强对习近平的忠诚度<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100372"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827252?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国领导人习近平晋升中国人民解放军火箭军新任司令员王厚斌和新任政治委员徐锡胜为上将军衔。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：李刚/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100372"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alastair-gale" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿拉斯泰尔·盖尔 (Alastair Gale)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chunhan-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">黄春汉 (Chun Han Wong)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 9:53（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国罢黜了导弹部队司令，分析人士称此举是为了确保军队对领导人习近平的忠诚，这支军队控制着针对美国的核弹头导弹，并将在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-china-ukraine-russia-hong-kong-military-war-517b87d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">任何夺取美国领土的企图</a>中发挥关键作用。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-china-ukraine-russia-hong-kong-military-war-517b87d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">台湾</a>通过武力。</p><p>中国人民解放军火箭军老兵李玉超的免职，标志着他在重要军事岗位上异常短暂的任期的突然结束，而几天前<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，中国又做出了一项神秘的决定，更换了外交部长</a>。</p><p>去年1月被任命为司令员的李已经好几个月没有在公开场合露面了。周二，中国庆祝中国人民解放军成立 96 周年，前一天举行的仪式上确认了他的下台。</p><p>在周二的周年纪念评论中，官方报纸《解放军报》敦促全体军人维护习近平作为共产党领导“核心”的地位，并坚持不懈地在军队内部执行纪律和反腐败工作。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">北京在周二的紧急会议上重新任命最高外交官王毅接替秦刚担任外交部长，但没有提及秦刚神秘缺席的问题。中国领导人习近平七个月前亲自挑选了秦国。照片：Florence Lo/Pool 路透社/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>据官方消息，在一天前的仪式上，习近平正式晋升中国人民解放军火箭军新任司令员王厚斌和新任政治委员徐锡胜为上将军衔，并向他们授予新军衔徽章。新华社．王和徐分别拥有海军和空军背景，他们的任命背离了中国战略导弹部队由具有该军种经验的军官指挥的长期做法。</p><p>麻省理工学院教授泰勒·弗拉维尔（Taylor Fravel）撰写了大量有关中国军队的文章，他表示，任命火箭军以外官员的决定表明，李所发现的问题非常严重，也反映了这支部队的重要性。在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与美国关系恶化的</a>情况下经历了显着扩张。</p><p>在中国对军队实行苏联式政治控制的情况下，解放军维持着双重领导体制，军事单位通常由两名同等级别的军官领导：一名指挥官，对作战决策拥有正式权力；以及执行党的指示的政委。</p><p>新华社的报道没有提及自 2020 年 7 月起担任这一职务的前任司令员李彦宏或政委。中国国防部没有立即回应有关李彦宏接任火箭军司令员的询问。</p><p>李克强离职几天前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国突然解除了</a>外交部长秦刚的职务，而就在秦刚上任几个月后，这是北京方面在没有任何解释的情况下做出的又一改变。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827253?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国最近解除了秦刚的外交部长职务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Thomas Trutschel/DPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>秦解职后不久，“对负责监督中国核武器计划的习近平心腹的前火箭军司令员李玉超的清洗，标志着中国多年来最深刻的领导层改组之一，”克雷格·辛格尔顿说。</p>保卫民主基金会的高级研究员，该基金会是一家总部位于华盛顿的保守派智囊团。<p></p><p>习近平于 2012 年底掌权后，在中国军队中开展了大范围的反腐败打击行动，清洗了多名高级指挥员，其中包括 2019 年被判处无期徒刑<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-chinese-military-chief-sentenced-to-life-in-prison-for-corruption-11550666372" target="_blank" class="icon none">的前联合参谋长房峰辉。</a>尽管近年来披露针对高级军官的调查的情况有所减少，但称这些清洗对于习近平将解放军打造成一支现代化战斗力量的努力至关重要。</p><p>辛格尔顿表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-wagner-revolt-questions-of-blame-in-vladimir-putins-inner-circle-64c541ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，俄罗斯最近发生的短暂武装起义</a>可能提醒人们需要严格控制军队。</p><p> “瓦格纳叛乱的失败几乎肯定强化了习近平对意识形态控制的执着，甚至不惜牺牲经济增长和中国正在进行的军事现代化，”他说。</p><p>解放军火箭军控制着中国的常规和核陆基导弹计划，包括能够到达美国本土的核弹头洲际弹道导弹。五角大楼在去年的一份报告中表示，北京近年来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-is-accelerating-its-nuclear-buildup-over-rising-fears-of-u-s-conflict-11649509201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加快了核武器的发展</a>，预计到 2035 年，拥有的核弹头将从目前的约 400 枚增至约 1,500 枚。</p><p>美国战略司令部司令在今年早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-has-more-icbm-launchers-than-u-s-american-military-reports-11675779463" target="_blank" class="icon none">给国会的一封信中写道</a>，中国在西部沙漠地区建造了巨大的洲际弹道导弹发射井，目前拥有的导弹发射装置比美国还多。</p><p>尽管习近平领导了中国军队总体规模的缩减，但解放军火箭军近年来有所壮大，这反映出其对北京利用远程核弹头弹道导弹威慑美国和发展常规导弹的战略的重要性用于任何地区冲突的武库。</p><p>根据<a href="https://nonproliferation.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/web_peoples_liberation_army_rocket_force_order_of_battle_07102023.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近的一项研究</a>，过去十年，中国的战斗导弹旅数量增加了一倍。</p><p>解放军火箭军拥有数百枚弹道导弹，可用于瞄准台湾，企图强行控制该岛或<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-missile-threat-drives-new-u-s-approach-in-asia-95fc9a7b" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁美国在日本和关岛的主要军事基地</a>。中国还部署了高超音速导弹，美国一直在努力开发这种导弹，而且导弹防御系统更难摧毁这种导弹。</p><p>中国人民解放军火箭军正在增强可信可靠的核威慑和反击能力，加强中远程精确打击力量，增强战略制衡能力，建设强大的现代化火箭军。 2019年最新的国防白皮书。</p><p>新的领导层任命标志着从军队其他部门引进指挥官的罕见决定。王新任火箭军司令员，曾任中国人民解放军海军副司令员。新任火箭军政委徐是一名空军军官，最近担任解放军南部战区副政委，该司令部负责南海地区，而南海是中美<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-jet-fighters-step-up-pressure-on-u-s-aircraft-over-south-china-sea-c2d1ac88" target="_blank" class="icon none">军事冲突频繁的</a>地区。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827254?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">北京阅兵式上展示的弹道导弹。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Mark Schiefelbein/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>关于李克强的副手刘广斌的命运也引发了猜测，他也已经几个月没有在公开场合露面了。官方媒体没有提及刘的地位，也没有提及任何替代者。</p><p>新的任命还意味着，火箭军现在有一位政治委员，其党龄高于指挥官，这是相当不寻常的。即将离任的司令员李和前政委徐忠波都是党的精英中央委员会的正式成员。</p><p>新任司令员王既不是中央委员，也不是无投票权的候补中央委员。新政委徐锡生是10月加入中央委员会的205名正式委员之一。</p><p>即使按照中国军方不透明的标准，与火箭军相关的细节也常常被严格隐瞒。</p><p>周一升职几天前，中国一家知名新闻媒体《澎湃新闻》援引已故军官的亲友的话称，一名前火箭军副司令于7月初去世，享年66岁。这份报告后来消失了。该报没有回应置评请求。</p><p>写信给 Alastair Gale <a href="mailto:alastair.gale@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（alastair.gale@wsj.com）</a>和 Chun Han Wong（ <a href="mailto:chunhan.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chunhan.wong@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 13:53:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b<author><![CDATA[Alastair GaleChun Han Wong]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Beijing Area Hit by Deadliest Flooding in a Decade]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>台风“多克苏里”横扫中国东部地区 至少20人死亡19人失踪<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100639"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=25BC57F5-3EBC-423B-9947-C966AF672A13&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbeijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">强台风给中国北方地区带来暴雨和严重洪涝灾害，造成北京及周边地区至少20人死亡。据中国官方媒体报道，数千人被迫逃离家园。照片：路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100639"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-liang" itemprop="url" rel="author">雷切尔·梁</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-strumpf" itemprop="url" rel="author">丹·斯特朗普夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 7:48 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>据官方媒体报道，台风“多克苏里”带来的暴雨造成洪水连续第四天，北京及周边地区至少有 20 人死亡，另有 19 人失踪。</p><p>截至周二，已有超过 5 万当地居民从家中撤离。据国有媒体《北京日报》报道，北京西部边缘的门头沟和房山郊区是受影响最严重的地区之一，一些地区报告出现电力和通讯中断。</p><p>据当地防洪抗旱办公室的一位官员称，截至早上 6 点，过去四天，这两个地区的降雨量已超过 16 英寸。这比他们预期的平均水平的一半以上，也超过了 2012 年该市上次<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443437504577545020100937242?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">重大洪水灾害的</a>水平，当时有 79 人死亡。</p><p>该市门头沟附近的斋堂水库自1998年建成以来首次放水，而一份官方报纸则刊登了洪水淹没北京郊区一家豪华酒店大堂的照片。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827281?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">台风“多克苏里”引发的洪水已淹没北京部分地区。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在袭击菲律宾和台湾后，多克苏里周五上午在福建省登陆，然后继续向北席卷，给首都带来了十年来最严重的降雨。据北京电台报道，到周二下午，风暴已向东北方向移动，并可能减弱。随着市政府降低应急响应级别，市中心的一些公园于下午晚些时候恢复运营。</p><p>中国沿海地区经常受到太平洋热带风暴的袭击，但多克苏里带来的降雨和洪水规模却不同寻常。除了周边的河北省（据报道有 9 人死亡、6 人失踪）和附近的港口城市天津外，风暴还给东北部约 600 英里的吉林省和广东省带来了大雨。据国家气象中心称，向南数千英里。</p><p>与此同时，据该中心称，第二场台风正在中国大陆沿海盘旋。该中心表示，预计卡努将在未来几天登陆浙江或福建地区，威胁进一步发生洪水，但北京面临的风险较低。</p><p>据中国官方新华社报道，上个月，西南特大城市重庆发生严重洪涝，造成 15 人死亡，造成广泛破坏，迫使数千人撤离家园。</p><p>重庆发生洪水之前，中国北方发生热浪，气温飙升至华氏100多度。据国营《环球时报》报道，中国国家气候中心上个月表示，中国出现了过去六十年来最高的高温天数，其中北京、邻近的天津和河北省遭受了最严重的高温。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827284?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Floodwaters swept through Miaofengshan, on the outskirts of Beijing, on Tuesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ng Han Guan/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Rachel Liang at <a href="mailto:rachel.liang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rachel.liang@wsj.com</a> and Dan Strumpf at <a href="mailto:Dan.Strumpf@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Dan.Strumpf@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc<author><![CDATA[Rachel LiangDan Strumpf]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>Floods/Tidal Waves</category><category> Hurricanes/Typhoons</category><category> Storms</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Weather</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>floods</category><category> tidal waves</category><category> hurricanes</category><category> typhoons</category><category> storms</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>weather </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Myanmar’s Aung San Suu Kyi Gets Surprise Partial Pardon]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Pardon extends to five convictions, including one about walkie talkies. But the former civilian leader will still serve decades for other offenses. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100460"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="613" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827248?width=860&amp;height=613" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The pardon would leave Aung San Suu Kyi to serve 27 years of incarceration.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: nyein chan naing/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100460"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/feliz-solomon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Feliz Solomon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 1, 2023 6:14 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Myanmar&#39;s former civilian leader Aung San Suu Kyi, who was ousted from power in a military coup in 2021 and convicted in a series of cases brought against her by the junta, was pardoned for some of those offenses, reducing her decadeslong sentence by six years.</p><p> Suu Kyi, 78 years old, was detained in an early morning raid on Feb. 1, 2021, when the military overthrew her elected government and plunged the Southeast Asian nation into turmoil. She was subsequently convicted of 18 charges, including corruption and election fraud, and sentenced to a total of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-to-serve-33-years-in-prison-after-series-of-trials-11672405999?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">33 years imprisonment.</a></p><p> In a statement disseminated on state-controlled media on Tuesday, the junta said Suu Kyi was granted a pardon for five of the offenses, including violating rules linked to the Covid-19 pandemic and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-myanmar-coup-aung-san-suu-kyi-accused-of-illegally-importing-walkie-talkies-11612361563?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">illegally importing walkie talkies</a> . Junta spokesman Zaw Min Tun told reporters the pardon would cut Suu Kyi&#39;s sentence by six years. That would leave her to serve 27 years of incarceration, unless the junta makes further changes or decisions involving her.</p><p> Her legal team hasn&#39;t been able to meet with her since December 2022 or confirm reports that Suu Kyi was recently moved from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-sansuukyis-life-in-myanmar-prison-no-visitors-calls-or-news-11667080016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">a prison in the capital, Naypyitaw</a> , to a house, said a person with knowledge of the matter. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827249?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Suu Kyi campaigning in Myanmar in 2015.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：str/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Suu Kyi&#39;s party, the National League for Democracy, swept historic elections in 2015, the country&#39;s first freely contested vote in a quarter-century, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-under-fire-abroad-wins-big-in-myanmar-election-11605248807?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was re-elected in a landslide</a> in 2020. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-the-generals-and-how-myanmars-democracy-hopes-collapsed-11612542400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The military staged a coup</a> hours before parliament was scheduled to convene for its first session after the election, detaining Suu Kyi and other officials including former President Win Myint, who was also granted a partial pardon Tuesday.</p><p> The military claimed the vote was marred by fraud, which election observers refuted.</p><p> Political analysts say the junta may be intending to appease foreign governments with Tuesday&#39;s partial pardons, offering a small gesture as a sign that they are open to change. Western governments, however, aren&#39;t likely to view the development as a real concession, the analysts said.</p><p> “I think we need to resist the temptation to read too much into it. If you look at all these charges, it seemed pretty clear that they were locking her up and throwing away the key,” said David Mathieson, an independent analyst based in Thailand who is an expert on Myanmar. “Shaving off six years just reveals that these were political show trials to begin with and there is no rule of law.”</p><p> The coup abruptly ended Myanmar&#39;s decadelong transition to democracy, returning the country to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmar-coup-poses-diplomatic-challenge-for-world-leaders-11613049643?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">global pariah status</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-economy-is-in-a-free-fall-with-empty-factories-closed-banks-failing-internet-11618059258?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sending its economy into a tailspin</a> as Western governments imposed sanctions and investors fled. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-new-generation-takes-the-lead-in-myanmar-protests-11615395087?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Mass street protests</a> , largely led by pro-democracy youths, were met with deadly force <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-new-generation-takes-the-lead-in-myanmar-protests-11615395087?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a> and soon gave way to armed rebellion.</p><p> Conflict between the junta and armed rebels has since spread throughout the country. The military has tried to eradicate opponents with escalating force, often <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmar-militarys-attack-leaves-village-in-ruins-strewn-with-charred-human-remains-7228843b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">using airstrikes to bomb villages</a> suspected of harboring rebels. On Monday, the junta extended a state of emergency, effectively postponing promised elections until next year, claiming it was necessary for stability.</p><p> More than 3,800 people have been killed since the coup and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-detained-by-myanmar-military-simply-disappearwhere-is-my-mom-11619265604?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">nearly 20,000 remain detained</a> , according to the Assistance Association for Political Prisoners, a nonprofit that monitors arrests and casualties. Politicians, artists, journalists and others are among those still behind bars.</p><p> Write to Feliz Solomon at <a href="mailto:feliz.solomon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">feliz.solomon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:14:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973<author><![CDATA[Feliz Solomon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Fraud</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>昂山素季</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>fraud</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[In Ukraine, Amputations Already Evoke Scale of World War I]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Tens of thousands estimated to have lost limbs since the start of the war, a toll not seen in recent armed conflicts in the West <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824318/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="自与俄罗斯的战争开始以来，有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去了一条或多条肢体，鲁斯兰娜·达尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 就是其中之一。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Ruslana Danilkina is one of between 20,000 and 50,000 Ukrainians who have lost one or more limbs since the start of the war with Russia. Vlada and Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS <span>Vlada and Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/bojan-pancevski" itemprop="url" rel="author">Bojan Pancevski</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 1, 2023 6:08 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> In February, Ruslana Danilkina, a 19-year-old Ukrainian soldier, came under fire near the front line around Zaporizhzhia in southeastern Ukraine. Shrapnel tore her left leg off above the knee. She clutched her severed thigh bone and watched medics place her severed leg into the vehicle that took her to a hospital.</p><p> “I was holding the bone in my hands… there and then I realized that this was the end, that my life would never be the same again,” Danilkina said.</p><p> Danilkina is one of between 20,000 and 50,000 Ukrainians who have lost one or more limbs since the start of the war, according to previously undisclosed estimates by prosthetics firms, doctors and charities.</p><p> The actual figure could be higher because it takes time to register patients after they undergo the procedure. Some are only amputated weeks or months after being wounded. And with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Kyiv&#39;s counteroffensive under way</a> , the war may be entering <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a more brutal phase</a> .</p><p> By comparison, some 67,000 Germans and 41,000 Britons had to have amputations during the course of World War I, when the procedure was often the only one available to prevent death. Fewer than 2,000 US veterans of the Afghanistan and Iraq invasions had amputations. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826535?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ottobock Chairman Hans Georg Näder with the company&#39;s top-of-the-range Genium artificial leg.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ottobock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Ukraine&#39;s government didn&#39;t immediately respond to a request for comment about the figures. Kyiv has kept precise casualty statistics secret so as not to demoralize the population. But even as a rough estimate, the number casts light on the staggering human cost of Russia&#39;s 17-month onslaught—a cost that will linger for decades.</p><p> Germany&#39;s Ottobock, the world&#39;s largest prosthetics manufacturer, which is working with Kyiv to help amputees, estimates the number of amputees at about 50,000 based on data from the government and medical partners. At the lower end, the Houp Foundation, a Kyiv-based charity, puts the number of serious injuries caused by the war at 200,000. About 10% of serious injuries typically require amputations, according to the foundation.</p><p> Such numbers reflect how Russia wages the war, with heavy use of mines and artillery, missile and drone attacks targeting soldiers and civilians alike.</p><p> “My grandfather founded our company in 1919 to help…German soldiers returning from World War I wounded by artillery fire, who lost their arms, legs or eyesight—this is exactly what we see in Ukraine,” said Hans Georg Näder, Ottobock&#39;s chairman.</p><p> Danilkina had five operations before receiving an artificial leg from Ottobock with the help of Superhumans, a charitable foundation based in the western city of Lviv.</p><p> She has since turned 20 and has been documenting her recovery on social media under the nickname Unbreakable Rusya. On Monday, she received a more sophisticated leg called Genium X3 developed by Ottobock with the US military that allows users to easily climb stairs or even walk backward. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824324?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Danilkina was injured near the front line in southeastern Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Vlada and Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Denys Kryvenko, a 24-year-old former steelworker from Kropyvnytskiy in central Ukraine, was drafted last year and lost both legs and his left arm in the battle for Bakhmut in January. Before the injury he was 6 feet 1 inch tall but now stands at 5 feet 6 inches on his artificial legs.</p><p> Both Kryvenko and Danilkina now work with Superhumans to help other amputees. Their social-network activism and media appearances have turned them into symbols of Ukrainian suffering and resilience.</p><p> Making enough artificial limbs, some of which cost over 50,000 euros, equivalent to around $55,000, isn&#39;t the main challenge: The bigger bottleneck is expert staff to care for amputees, each of whom needs a tailor-made prosthetic, Näder said. Kyiv pays up to €20,000 per military amputee but civilians often struggle to afford treatment. Ottobock grants a discount for Ukrainians and provides free training for doctors and technicians there. Still, many patients must rely on charities to obtain prostheses.</p><p> Before the Russian invasion last year, Ukraine had several thousand amputations annually, but its healthcare system is now overwhelmed, according to Ukrainian doctors and specialist clinics, with many patients waiting more than a year for a new limb. Doctors in Lviv alone performed over 53,000 surgeries in the past year, said Oleksandr Kobzarev, an executive with Unbroken, a network of medical rehabilitation centers. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="867" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826537?width=700&amp;height=867" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ukrainian soldier Denys Kryvenko, who has lost both legs and an arm, with a medic following surgery in a military hospital in Vinnytsia, Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Denys Kryvenko </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="704" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826533?width=700&amp;height=704" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Denys Kryvenko in a therapy session with Ruslana Danilkina at the Superhumans rehabilitation center in Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Denys Kryvenko</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Superhumans chief executive Olga Rudneva says her foundation only has the capacity to admit some 50 amputees each month. She estimates the number of amputees as at least 20,000 since last year.</p><p> Patients should get new limbs at the latest 90 days after amputation to avoid atrophy and other problems, Rudneva said, but many have waited for over a year. Young children among the amputees are particularly difficult to care for, she said, because they must change several prostheses by the time they become adults.</p><p> Oleksandra Paskal, 7, lost her leg in a Russian missile attack near Odesa in May 2022. Her mother Maria, who partially lost her hearing in the explosion, says her daughter is woken at night by phantom pain in the lost limb—a frequent neurological condition in amputees.</p><p> Dr. Jennifer Ernst, head of the Innovative Amputation Medicine department at the Hannover University Hospital in Germany, specializes in bionic surgery involving connecting nerves to prosthetic limbs. She recently operated on a soldier who lost both legs in an attack that killed his entire unit.</p><p> Like many Ukrainian patients evacuated abroad after serious trauma, the soldier had an antibiotic-resistant bacterial infection, forcing Ernst to remove significant pieces of leg tissue. Despite successes—one patient&#39;s arm was saved by a 3D-printed bone implant—she says most have to be amputated because of advanced infections.</p><p> Last year, her clinic admitted a 16-year-old boy who lost an arm when a Russian missile hit a Kyiv metro station. The blast killed his younger sister but left their mother only lightly injured. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824387?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Oleksandra Paskal, 7, lost her leg in a Russian missile attack near Odesa in May 2022.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Odessa City Council</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Out of 100 soldiers wounded within about 3 miles of the front line, 36% suffered very severe injuries, while between 5% and 10% of all deployed troops were killed, according to Ukrainian military estimates shared with a group of US military surgeons. In comparison, only 1.3% to 2% of US troops deployed in recent conflicts died in action.</p><p> Western military surgeons haven&#39;t seen such injuries on this scale since World War II, said Dr. Aaron Epstein, head of the Global Surgical and Medical Support Group of former military surgeons who train Ukrainian military medics.</p><p> While artillery and missiles were the main causes of amputation early in the conflict, some of the worst casualties now come from mines laid along the 600-mile front line. Between 40 and 80 patients report to hospitals in the city of Zaporizhzhia with traumas each day, including amputees coming from the front line some 25 miles away, said Dr. Kostyantyn Mylytsya, medical director of the private KSM Clinic. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B4EEDAEB-204A-4D35-A945-2EA739618C35&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fin-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Storm Shadow missiles equip Ukraine&#39;s counteroffensive with the ability to hit Russian targets far behind the front lines. The WSJ explores how the weapon works and why it&#39;s forcing Moscow to rethink its logistics. Photo Illustration: Nayon Cho<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Mylytsya focused on cosmetic surgery before the war. Now his clinic treats and rehabilitates amputees. Such centers, he says, are needed “in every town across Ukraine; they must be as common as dentists.”</p><p> A former British paratrooper serving in Ukraine&#39;s armed forces lost his foot in a mine explosion in June. He had previously been wounded in April last year, a month after volunteering to fight, when a Russian cruise missile hit his unit&#39;s headquarters. He spent five months in Ukrainian and British hospitals but returned to the southern front as soon as he could.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What will the long term effects of the war be on Ukrainians?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> In June, his unit launched a nightly raid on Russian forces but suffered devastating losses. His team spent the night cowering in the basement of an abandoned school before attacking again. They drove past destroyed Western Leopard tanks, Humvees and Bradley infantry fighting vehicles. The severed limbs of their comrades lay scattered on the ground.</p><p> The soldiers used broken sticks to tap their way forward to detect hidden mines. As he was setting up a machine gun near an abandoned Russian trench, the 28-year-old stepped on an antipersonnel mine.</p><p> “I screamed and fell in the direction of travel, and I was lucky not to hit another mine,” he said.</p><p> He was evacuated to a field hospital where doctors saved his leg but cut off most of his left foot. He said many in his unit were hospitalized after the raid. Most of the soldiers who accompanied them died.</p><p> Now, waiting for treatment in the US, he said he intends to return to his regiment—even if only as an instructor.</p><p> “This war is horrendous and now I, too, am crippled…But I don&#39;t regret it,” he said.</p><p> Write to Bojan Pancevski at <a href="mailto:bojan.pancevski@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">bojan.pancevski@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:08:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320<author><![CDATA[Bojan Pancevski]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>Medical Equipment/Supplies</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>Medical Devices/Apparatus</category><category> Orthopedic/Prosthetic Implants/Devices</category><category> Diagnostic/Therapeutic Devices</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>健康</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>医疗/程序</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>健康</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>医疗</category><category>程序</category><category>军事行动</category><category>medical equipment</category><category> supplies</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>medical devices</category><category> apparatus</category><category> orthopedic</category><category> prosthetic implants</category><category> devices</category><category> diagnostic</category><category> therapeutic devices </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[In Ukraine, Amputations Already Evoke Scale of World War I]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Tens of thousands estimated to have lost limbs since the start of the war, a toll not seen in recent armed conflicts in the West <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824318/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="自与俄罗斯的战争开始以来，有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去了一条或多条肢体，鲁斯兰娜·达尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 就是其中之一。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Ruslana Danilkina is one of between 20,000 and 50,000 Ukrainians who have lost one or more limbs since the start of the war with Russia. Vlada and Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS <span>Vlada and Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/bojan-pancevski" itemprop="url" rel="author">Bojan Pancevski</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 1, 2023 6:08 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> In February, Ruslana Danilkina, a 19-year-old Ukrainian soldier, came under fire near the front line around Zaporizhzhia in southeastern Ukraine. Shrapnel tore her left leg off above the knee. She clutched her severed thigh bone and watched medics place her severed leg into the vehicle that took her to a hospital.</p><p> “I was holding the bone in my hands… there and then I realized that this was the end, that my life would never be the same again,” Danilkina said.</p><p> Danilkina is one of between 20,000 and 50,000 Ukrainians who have lost one or more limbs since the start of the war, according to previously undisclosed estimates by prosthetics firms, doctors and charities.</p><p> The actual figure could be higher because it takes time to register patients after they undergo the procedure. Some are only amputated weeks or months after being wounded. And with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Kyiv&#39;s counteroffensive under way</a> , the war may be entering <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a more brutal phase</a> .</p><p> By comparison, some 67,000 Germans and 41,000 Britons had to have amputations during the course of World War I, when the procedure was often the only one available to prevent death. Fewer than 2,000 US veterans of the Afghanistan and Iraq invasions had amputations. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826535?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ottobock Chairman Hans Georg Näder with the company&#39;s top-of-the-range Genium artificial leg.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ottobock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Ukraine&#39;s government didn&#39;t immediately respond to a request for comment about the figures. Kyiv has kept precise casualty statistics secret so as not to demoralize the population. But even as a rough estimate, the number casts light on the staggering human cost of Russia&#39;s 17-month onslaught—a cost that will linger for decades.</p><p> Germany&#39;s Ottobock, the world&#39;s largest prosthetics manufacturer, which is working with Kyiv to help amputees, estimates the number of amputees at about 50,000 based on data from the government and medical partners. At the lower end, the Houp Foundation, a Kyiv-based charity, puts the number of serious injuries caused by the war at 200,000. About 10% of serious injuries typically require amputations, according to the foundation.</p><p> Such numbers reflect how Russia wages the war, with heavy use of mines and artillery, missile and drone attacks targeting soldiers and civilians alike.</p><p> “My grandfather founded our company in 1919 to help…German soldiers returning from World War I wounded by artillery fire, who lost their arms, legs or eyesight—this is exactly what we see in Ukraine,” said Hans Georg Näder, Ottobock&#39;s chairman.</p><p> Danilkina had five operations before receiving an artificial leg from Ottobock with the help of Superhumans, a charitable foundation based in the western city of Lviv.</p><p> She has since turned 20 and has been documenting her recovery on social media under the nickname Unbreakable Rusya. On Monday, she received a more sophisticated leg called Genium X3 developed by Ottobock with the US military that allows users to easily climb stairs or even walk backward. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824324?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Danilkina was injured near the front line in southeastern Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Vlada and Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Denys Kryvenko, a 24-year-old former steelworker from Kropyvnytskiy in central Ukraine, was drafted last year and lost both legs and his left arm in the battle for Bakhmut in January. Before the injury he was 6 feet 1 inch tall but now stands at 5 feet 6 inches on his artificial legs.</p><p> Both Kryvenko and Danilkina now work with Superhumans to help other amputees. Their social-network activism and media appearances have turned them into symbols of Ukrainian suffering and resilience.</p><p> Making enough artificial limbs, some of which cost over 50,000 euros, equivalent to around $55,000, isn&#39;t the main challenge: The bigger bottleneck is expert staff to care for amputees, each of whom needs a tailor-made prosthetic, Näder said. Kyiv pays up to €20,000 per military amputee but civilians often struggle to afford treatment. Ottobock grants a discount for Ukrainians and provides free training for doctors and technicians there. Still, many patients must rely on charities to obtain prostheses.</p><p> Before the Russian invasion last year, Ukraine had several thousand amputations annually, but its healthcare system is now overwhelmed, according to Ukrainian doctors and specialist clinics, with many patients waiting more than a year for a new limb. Doctors in Lviv alone performed over 53,000 surgeries in the past year, said Oleksandr Kobzarev, an executive with Unbroken, a network of medical rehabilitation centers. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="867" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826537?width=700&amp;height=867" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ukrainian soldier Denys Kryvenko, who has lost both legs and an arm, with a medic following surgery in a military hospital in Vinnytsia, Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Denys Kryvenko </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="704" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826533?width=700&amp;height=704" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Denys Kryvenko in a therapy session with Ruslana Danilkina at the Superhumans rehabilitation center in Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Denys Kryvenko</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Superhumans chief executive Olga Rudneva says her foundation only has the capacity to admit some 50 amputees each month. She estimates the number of amputees as at least 20,000 since last year.</p><p> Patients should get new limbs at the latest 90 days after amputation to avoid atrophy and other problems, Rudneva said, but many have waited for over a year. Young children among the amputees are particularly difficult to care for, she said, because they must change several prostheses by the time they become adults.</p><p> Oleksandra Paskal, 7, lost her leg in a Russian missile attack near Odesa in May 2022. Her mother Maria, who partially lost her hearing in the explosion, says her daughter is woken at night by phantom pain in the lost limb—a frequent neurological condition in amputees.</p><p> Dr. Jennifer Ernst, head of the Innovative Amputation Medicine department at the Hannover University Hospital in Germany, specializes in bionic surgery involving connecting nerves to prosthetic limbs. She recently operated on a soldier who lost both legs in an attack that killed his entire unit.</p><p> Like many Ukrainian patients evacuated abroad after serious trauma, the soldier had an antibiotic-resistant bacterial infection, forcing Ernst to remove significant pieces of leg tissue. Despite successes—one patient&#39;s arm was saved by a 3D-printed bone implant—she says most have to be amputated because of advanced infections.</p><p> Last year, her clinic admitted a 16-year-old boy who lost an arm when a Russian missile hit a Kyiv metro station. The blast killed his younger sister but left their mother only lightly injured. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824387?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Oleksandra Paskal, 7, lost her leg in a Russian missile attack near Odesa in May 2022.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Odessa City Council</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Out of 100 soldiers wounded within about 3 miles of the front line, 36% suffered very severe injuries, while between 5% and 10% of all deployed troops were killed, according to Ukrainian military estimates shared with a group of US military surgeons. In comparison, only 1.3% to 2% of US troops deployed in recent conflicts died in action.</p><p> Western military surgeons haven&#39;t seen such injuries on this scale since World War II, said Dr. Aaron Epstein, head of the Global Surgical and Medical Support Group of former military surgeons who train Ukrainian military medics.</p><p> While artillery and missiles were the main causes of amputation early in the conflict, some of the worst casualties now come from mines laid along the 600-mile front line. Between 40 and 80 patients report to hospitals in the city of Zaporizhzhia with traumas each day, including amputees coming from the front line some 25 miles away, said Dr. Kostyantyn Mylytsya, medical director of the private KSM Clinic. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B4EEDAEB-204A-4D35-A945-2EA739618C35&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fin-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Storm Shadow missiles equip Ukraine&#39;s counteroffensive with the ability to hit Russian targets far behind the front lines. The WSJ explores how the weapon works and why it&#39;s forcing Moscow to rethink its logistics. Photo Illustration: Nayon Cho<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Mylytsya focused on cosmetic surgery before the war. Now his clinic treats and rehabilitates amputees. Such centers, he says, are needed “in every town across Ukraine; they must be as common as dentists.”</p><p> A former British paratrooper serving in Ukraine&#39;s armed forces lost his foot in a mine explosion in June. He had previously been wounded in April last year, a month after volunteering to fight, when a Russian cruise missile hit his unit&#39;s headquarters. He spent five months in Ukrainian and British hospitals but returned to the southern front as soon as he could.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
